</html></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Drew Davis</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#333333>(2/2/01 4:55:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Pet Control</span><hr size=1> <br>
&gt;How do I tell when a pet is &quot;mezzed&quot; and when it is <br>
&gt;not?<br>
<br>
   I assume you mean a monster.  Your pet won't be getting mezzed by the enchanter.<br>
<br>
   If the mob is mezzed, it'll just be standing around doing nothing.  If it's not pounding on someone, leave it alone.  An enchanter will generally take all but one out.  Good pullers will pull the one main target a bit to the side after a mez, to seperate it from the big pile of mezzed ones, making it easier for everyone to target.<br>
<br>
&gt;And I also played with a Bard to stated when a battle <br>
&gt;started an 'auto message' that the mob was 'snared'. <br>
&gt;What do I do? How do I know that this is done and <br>
&gt;will my pet break both of these?<br>
<br>
   Your pet will not break snare.  The earth pet root spell used to replace (overwrite) snare, which made them unpopular in groups.<br>
<br>
   The &quot;auto messages&quot; can be confusing, simply because spells get resisted.  I'm not fond of people that put such a message in a hotkey with a &quot;cast&quot; button, because then when you see &quot;a %t has been snared/malised/whatevered&quot;, you still don't know if it's true.  It's better to only send such a comment after a successful command.  I know you're going to _try_ to snare/malise/whatever, and I can see the spell effects.  The only thing I don't know is whether or not it was resisted.  That's the thing to tell party members, not the fact that you're casting.<br>
<br>
&gt; From the above good remarks I can see that I should <br>
&gt; sit with my pet in the BACK of our group and wait to <br>
&gt; send my pet in AFTER the battle starts and ONLY to <br>
&gt; the mob that the main tank is fighting. Am I correct? <br>
<br>
   That's more or less the idea, yes <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Keeping the pet in the back of the group can help keep incoming critters from beating on it.  Staying in the back of the group yourself helps keep them from beating on you.<br>
<br>
    The /assist command has various quirks and bugs, and depending on your puller's technique may not be that reliable until you're actually in the fight.  Any group (with enchanters or not) should have a designated &quot;assistee&quot; whose job it is to pick targets.  That's usually the puller, or a secondary tank.  The most efficient way to fight almost any battle is to take down one target at a time, as quickly as possible, rather than spread your attacks around.  Consider that wounded creatures still do full damage; the way to reduce the damage your party takes is to kill them, while hurting them does nothing.  One dead and one full health critter hurts less than two half-health critter.  Generally, people prefer to take down the spellcasters before the melee-type mobs.  (Sometimes, groups will prefer a different order, say if they can keep a caster mezzed easier than the warrior, so they attack the warrior first.)  Good communication is important.  But generally, as a mage, you'll just be following the main assist's choices.<br>
<br>
   The various forms of &quot;crowd control&quot; (mez, root parking, one kind of kiting, or sometimes even using the pet to occupy a second target) are all just ways of getting one or more creatures out of the battle without killing it, while you work on one of them.  If you have to kill two things, you'd rather do it one right after the other.  If you fight both, one hits you for the amount of time to kill it, while the other hits you for twice the amount of time to kill it, for 3x damage.  If you mez or park one, the first one hits you, then you let mez wear off, then the second one hits you, for 2x damage.  Keeping the monsters from hitting you is the flip side of you hitting them.<br>
<br>
&gt;Also, what does the /pet as you were....statement <br>
&gt;make my pet do? <br>
<br>
   It just wipes your pet's memory, returning him to<br>
a nice neutral state as though you had just summoned it.  It will forget all about anything it had been ordered to attack, anything that hit it, where you last told it to guard, etc.  It's useful in pet control situations to clear the pet's &quot;hate list&quot; of things that have taken a swing at it, so the pet won't automatically move on to the next thing on its list.<br>
<br>
