<br>
1. Pay attention<br>
2. Avoid getting any mob aggro on you.<br>
3. Making sure pet stays on the proper mob with proper use of /pet back off and /assist.<br>
<br>
There are a lot of other things that can help. Such as knowing pathing, timing /pet back off with mez/stuns, using /pet guard here and so forth. However those top three are in my opinion the most important. <p>Zurrin Zypher <BR>
59th Mage of Saryrn</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ucydmab.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cydmab</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#333333>(6/8/01 4:57:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mages who brag about controling their pet</span><hr size=1> Once you have CoH, if the pet goes runs off into the dungeon and is attacking something, step away from the group if possible, and CoH yourself. This will kill your pet AND clear your aggro. Using earthen boots after your pet has engaged something far from the group may be suicide (although steping away from the group and letting the resulting train just kill you is a good idea too... or gate if you can get back to the group quickly).<br>
<br>
Never use /assist until you see the mob life bar go down.<br>
<br>
Not sure if this was said, but when a add mob hits you while your pet is attacking something, say /g add, wait patiently for the chanter to mez it, then hit /pet back off. In that order. If you hit back off too soon the mob will hit you again and your pet will attack the add.<br>
<br>
Except for the above case, when in doubt tap /pet back off every once in awhile.<br>
<br>
Just before a mob dies, tap /pet back off just in case. Pet may have some aggro on a mezzed mob while you weren't looking and will switch targets right when the current one dies.<br>
<br>
If you are really feeling like a super man and the pet is on the wrong target, you can hit /pet back off between monster swings while the chanter is casting mez. Only do this if your chanter can't or won't stun though, and if you are really with it and have no lag. Quite frankly I just spam /back off and hope the chanter stuns first or I back it off with enough time to get the mez on. <br>
<br>
Finally, if you have your epic pet or a very strong pet relative to the mobs, sometimes you just say &quot;%$$% it&quot; and let the pet solo an add its stuck on. Make sure you tell your chanter that you might do this before the group starts, and say /g pet mezzing %t whenever you give up controlling the epic. A healthy buffed epic can easily solo a mob below level 51. If you don't have an epic and the pet is stubborn, click your earthen boots.<br>
